==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stive
<hw>Stive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Stived</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stiving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Probably fr. F.
<ets>estiver</ets> to compress, stow, L. <ets>stipare</ets>: cf. It.
<ets>stivare</ets>, Sp. <ets>estivar</ets>. Cf. <er>Stevedore</er>,
<er>Stiff</er>.]</ety> <def>To stuff; to crowd; to fill full; hence, to
make hot and close; to render stifling.</def>
<rj><au>Sandys.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His chamber was commonly <qex>stived</qex> with friends or suitors
of one kind or other.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H. Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stive</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stive
<hw>Stive</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be stifled or
suffocated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stive</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stive
<hw>Stive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The floating dust in flour mills
caused by the operation or grinding.</def> <rj><au>De
Colange.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stiver</ent>⟦br⟧
